    "stress_mark": "ˈ",
    "notes": "Medieval Portuguese stress: paroxytone default; grave accent (à) marks stress override. Early medieval orthography did not write the acute or circumflex, but when a modern-normalised input carries them they must attract stress rather than be dropped, so the acute/circumflex vowels join the marked set on the same front/back axis as their base letters. DIPHTHONGS: declared so the bundled syllabifier counts nuclei correctly — without them every vowel run merges into one nucleus and co-e-lho is read as coe-lho, one syllable short, putting the stress and its vowel reduction on the wrong vowel. ⟨oe⟩ is hiatus, not a diphthong (Cunha & Cintra, §Ditongos).",
